al film, novels, sculptures, images, dance, performances, and anecdotes. In doing so, she argues for the importance of differential embodiment and movement to the creation and survival of Black sociality, and refutes stereotypic notions of Africa as less progressive than the West in recognizing the rights of disabled people. Ultimately, this book foregrounds the engagement of diasporic Africans, who are still reeling from the violence of colonialism, slavery, poverty, and war, as they gesture toward a liberatory Black sociality by falling, floating, and flickering.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aDisability studies. 0aPeople with disabilities. 0aWomanism. 7aART / Performance.2bisacsh  aAfrican Diaspora.  aAmputees.  aAngola.  aAppropriation.  aArt.  aAsthma.  aAutism.  aBlack sociality.  aChild Soldiers.  aConjoinment.  aControl.  aCripistemology.  aDiagnosis.  aDifferential embodiment.  aDisability.  aDrowned.  aEnfreakment.  aEye Floaters.  aFalling.  aFlickering.  aFloating.  aFungibility.  aHaptic.  aHorizontality.  aHuman-Animal Hybrid.  aIntersensorial.  aKuduro.  aLandmines.  aMediterranean.  aMermaids.  aMovement.  aNeurocacophony.  aNeurodiversity.  aNon-normative.  aPerformance.  aPolio.  aQueer.  aSierra Leone.  aSouth Africa.  aSpasm.  aStuttering.  aThe black body.  aTransgender.  aUnhinging.  aZombie.  aZoos.  acrawling.  afilm.  amotion.  amusic videos.  avision.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075163540uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479818471.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479818471423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479818471/original  a978-3-11-075